00:10:40.920 --> 00:10:42.840
It's interesting if you
look at what happened.

00:10:42.840 --> 00:10:44.670
We had text messaging, right?

00:10:44.670 --> 00:10:46.740
And then you had over
the top messaging

00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:49.590
services like iMessage,
WhatsApp, Signal, et cetera.

00:10:49.590 --> 00:10:52.297
And they pushed far
ahead of text messaging.

00:10:52.297 --> 00:10:54.630
They didn't have restrictions,
they had more multimedia,

00:10:54.630 --> 00:10:56.297
you could see when
the person is typing,

00:10:56.297 --> 00:10:58.270
you get read receipts,
all that kind of stuff.

00:10:58.270 --> 00:10:59.812
And so what's happened
is regular SMS

00:10:59.812 --> 00:11:00.870
has got left behind.

00:11:00.870 --> 00:11:03.120
And the work that we've been
doing-- and you're right,

00:11:03.120 --> 00:11:04.230
I was going to say RCS--

00:11:04.230 --> 00:11:07.230
this is the new IMS standard.

00:11:07.230 --> 00:11:10.020
We've been working on that
and working with carriers

00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:12.810
and working with device
makers to basically bring SMS

00:11:12.810 --> 00:11:15.960
up to that level so
that that capability is

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:19.230
available in your
phone and it becomes

00:11:19.230 --> 00:11:21.040
more standard, effectively.

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:23.920
And so that's the approach
that we've been taking.

00:11:23.920 --> 00:11:27.870
But it takes time to work
through all the carrier

00:11:27.870 --> 00:11:30.750
standards and to get adoption.

00:11:30.750 --> 00:11:33.510
