00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:03.890
you think about
selecting between

00:16:03.890 --> 00:16:05.190
these various technologies.

00:16:05.190 --> 00:16:07.190
At the end of the day,
the way we think about it

00:16:07.190 --> 00:16:10.790
is that we want developers to
have the flexibility to choose

00:16:10.790 --> 00:16:12.740
the right technology for them.

00:16:12.740 --> 00:16:14.810
And for developers-- a
perfect example of this

00:16:14.810 --> 00:16:19.050
is for games, where there is
no real mobile web equivalent.

00:16:19.050 --> 00:16:21.050
So we want to make sure
you have the flexibility

00:16:21.050 --> 00:16:22.940
to do what's right for
you and for companies who

00:16:22.940 --> 00:16:24.690
are mobile first, then
are really thinking

00:16:24.690 --> 00:16:26.888
about building native apps.

00:16:26.888 --> 00:16:29.180
We want to make sure that
they have the same capability

00:16:29.180 --> 00:16:32.090
to bring that instant-like
experience to mobile web

00:16:32.090 --> 00:16:34.670
traffic or to even the Play
Store, like we talked about

00:16:34.670 --> 00:16:36.440
at the keynotes.

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:38.150
And then if you're
on the web and you

00:16:38.150 --> 00:16:39.830
want to focus on PWA
or AMP, you know,

00:16:39.830 --> 00:16:42.740
there are pros and cons of all
of these various approaches.

00:16:42.740 --> 00:16:46.070
So it's kind of about what's
right for you as a developer.

