00:20:52.540 --> 00:20:57.070
AUDIENCE: What can you or
the community do to help--

00:20:57.070 --> 00:20:58.900
CHET HAASE: To simplify?

00:20:58.900 --> 00:21:00.180
STEPHANIE CUTHBERTSON: It's
a great question, actually.

00:21:00.180 --> 00:21:01.430
I don't know how many of you--

00:21:01.430 --> 00:21:04.577
there was in Android Studio
AMA a month or two ago,

00:21:04.577 --> 00:21:05.660
and this question came up.

00:21:05.660 --> 00:21:06.370
I thought it was a great one.

00:21:06.370 --> 00:21:08.350
Essentially people
saying, look, it's

00:21:08.350 --> 00:21:10.820
great that you're making
development better.

00:21:10.820 --> 00:21:13.767
But you've made it better, and
now there's all this new stuff,

00:21:13.767 --> 00:21:15.350
and I have to learn
all the new stuff.

00:21:15.350 --> 00:21:18.950
And so holy cow, I got to
onboard everybody to this.

00:21:18.950 --> 00:21:22.000
And so yes, we've been talking
about this a lot in our team

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:26.200
is how do we not just add
documentation and samples,

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:28.860
but holistically revamp
everything we have.

00:21:28.860 --> 00:21:30.710
So let me try this out on you.

00:21:30.710 --> 00:21:33.693
Wouldn't it be cool if you
could come into Android,

00:21:33.693 --> 00:21:35.860
and instead of having to
go through what I sometimes

00:21:35.860 --> 00:21:38.980
call the layer cake of like
API 9 and 10 and 11 and 12,

00:21:38.980 --> 00:21:42.413
by the time you have read all
the documents about how it

00:21:42.413 --> 00:21:44.080
works on different
versions, you kind of

00:21:44.080 --> 00:21:45.580
forgot where you started.

00:21:45.580 --> 00:21:47.080
You could say like
look, I just want

00:21:47.080 --> 00:21:49.163
to manage a background task.

00:21:49.163 --> 00:21:51.580
Send me to the documentation
that tells me how to do that.

00:21:51.580 --> 00:21:53.610
Look, I just want
to build some UI.

00:21:53.610 --> 00:21:54.860
Just want to build navigation.

00:21:54.860 --> 00:21:56.610
And I think we're
thinking a lot about how

00:21:56.610 --> 00:21:59.980
to improve all of our
documentation and samples

00:21:59.980 --> 00:22:02.190
and other supporting
information around that,

00:22:02.190 --> 00:22:03.565
as well as I think
the work Yigit

00:22:03.565 --> 00:22:05.290
and the team have done
around simplifying

00:22:05.290 --> 00:22:06.700
the libraries has just been--

00:22:06.700 --> 00:22:09.440
I mean, I'm probably biased,
but I think it's amazing.

00:22:09.440 --> 00:22:11.325
So I think we're
thinking a lot about how

00:22:11.325 --> 00:22:12.700
to lower that
barrier to entry so

00:22:12.700 --> 00:22:14.783
that when people are newer
to Android development,

00:22:14.783 --> 00:22:15.800
it's straightforward.

00:22:15.800 --> 00:22:17.560
I would love feedback
about what's working

00:22:17.560 --> 00:22:18.942
and also what we can do better.

00:22:18.942 --> 00:22:19.692
AUDIENCE: Awesome.

00:22:19.692 --> 00:22:20.738
Thank you.

00:22:20.738 --> 00:22:21.530
CHET HAASE: Thanks.

00:22:21.530 --> 00:22:23.405
Actually, I would add
too, part of this stuff

00:22:23.405 --> 00:22:25.850
that Yigit and team
were working on

00:22:25.850 --> 00:22:27.330
was the opinionated
guide, right?

00:22:27.330 --> 00:22:28.770
And it's trying to address that.

00:22:28.770 --> 00:22:30.920
It's not just the
libraries, but it's also

00:22:30.920 --> 00:22:33.003
how do you put these things
together and architect

00:22:33.003 --> 00:22:34.320
or application appropriately.

00:22:34.320 --> 00:22:36.070
So hopefully we're
getting better at that.

00:22:36.070 --> 00:22:38.390
I would argue that
we're not done.

00:22:38.390 --> 00:22:40.820
YIGIT BOYAR: It's also
like we're trying our best.

00:22:40.820 --> 00:22:42.300
It's also a little
bit challenging,

00:22:42.300 --> 00:22:45.580
because like you know
your use case the best.

00:22:45.580 --> 00:22:48.170
So it's very hard to give
super generic advice.

00:22:48.170 --> 00:22:51.420
So we're trying to learn this
over the last two, three years.

00:22:51.420 --> 00:22:53.560
I think we got better.

00:22:53.560 --> 00:22:54.920
to work with the community.

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:57.260
Now we moved Composed
to the open source,

00:22:57.260 --> 00:23:00.620
we got a lot more code reviews
and help from the community.

00:23:00.620 --> 00:23:04.760
And I think if we can work
together with you all engineers

00:23:04.760 --> 00:23:07.520
and people in our team,
that will get a lot better

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:08.480
over time.

00:23:08.480 --> 00:23:09.980
STEPHANIE CUTHBERTSON:
Yeah, Jetpack

00:23:09.980 --> 00:23:12.300
is intended to be our
opinionated answer.

00:23:12.300 --> 00:23:14.285
It's kind of the one, two--

00:23:14.285 --> 00:23:16.160
remember Dianne wrote
that really famous post

00:23:16.160 --> 00:23:18.080
that we're not opinionated,
to which you all

00:23:18.080 --> 00:23:21.320
replied please be opinionated?

00:23:21.320 --> 00:23:23.660
And that's basically
what Jetpack is, and we

00:23:23.660 --> 00:23:26.702
want to keep building
on that so that you

00:23:26.702 --> 00:23:28.160
do have a sense of
like, look, this

00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:29.535
is the way we
recommend doing it.

00:23:29.535 --> 00:23:31.198
You can always drop
down to the raw--

00:23:31.198 --> 00:23:33.740
we sometimes call the laws of
gravity-- to the raw framework.

00:23:33.740 --> 00:23:35.365
We always want to
leave you that power.

00:23:35.365 --> 00:23:37.730
But also provide a
more elegant, fast way

00:23:37.730 --> 00:23:40.048
of getting things done.

00:23:40.048 --> 00:23:42.590
CHET HAASE: All right, I'm going
to dip into online questions

00:23:42.590 --> 00:23:42.890
here.

00:23:42.890 --> 00:23:44.990
