00:30:35.170 --> 00:30:38.570
that not much
innovation remains?

00:30:38.570 --> 00:30:40.070
DIANNE HACKBORN:
Very good question.

00:30:40.070 --> 00:30:43.450
So first of all, I understand
it is really painful

00:30:43.450 --> 00:30:47.110
when we change things
like this and remove

00:30:47.110 --> 00:30:48.850
some of the freedom
you have to do things

00:30:48.850 --> 00:30:51.408
and put more
[INAUDIBLE] things on.

00:30:51.408 --> 00:30:53.200
It's also very important,
and it's actually

00:30:53.200 --> 00:30:56.650
been kind of a fundamental part
of Android from the beginning.

00:30:56.650 --> 00:31:00.753
When we first did Android,
we had application sandboxing

00:31:00.753 --> 00:31:02.170
from the very
beginning, which was

00:31:02.170 --> 00:31:05.510
a huge change from how
operating systems traditionally

00:31:05.510 --> 00:31:06.010
have worked.

00:31:06.010 --> 00:31:08.500
It greatly restricts
applications.

00:31:08.500 --> 00:31:10.620
And it's very
important for us so

00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:14.200
that we have this balance
between freedom of developers,

00:31:14.200 --> 00:31:16.420
how open of an
ecosystem we can have,

00:31:16.420 --> 00:31:18.430
and what the user experience is.

00:31:18.430 --> 00:31:20.500
And so things like
application sandboxing

00:31:20.500 --> 00:31:23.620
allowed us to do things
like by having restrictions

00:31:23.620 --> 00:31:27.160
in the platform, we can have
a more open ecosystem instead

00:31:27.160 --> 00:31:30.160
of having something like
where someone is sitting there

00:31:30.160 --> 00:31:32.860
approving every
single application,

00:31:32.860 --> 00:31:35.950
like with arbitrary rules about
whether it could be installed.

00:31:35.950 --> 00:31:37.360
We can have a more
open store, we

00:31:37.360 --> 00:31:39.130
can have side loading
of applications

00:31:39.130 --> 00:31:40.990
and that kind of stuff.

00:31:40.990 --> 00:31:42.898
And we are always
having to kind of find

00:31:42.898 --> 00:31:44.190
a balance between these things.

00:31:44.190 --> 00:31:47.020
So as our ecosystem
grows and changes,

00:31:47.020 --> 00:31:49.690
problems come up where we
have issues, especially

00:31:49.690 --> 00:31:51.230
around user experience.

00:31:51.230 --> 00:31:55.770
So for a good example of this
is background restrictions.

00:31:55.770 --> 00:31:59.050
We're finding that increasingly,
battery life on the devices

00:31:59.050 --> 00:32:02.000
was getting bad because
applications had total freedom

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:03.250
to do stuff in the background.

00:32:03.250 --> 00:32:04.960
And you give them
freedom to do stuff,

00:32:04.960 --> 00:32:06.290
and they're going to do it.

00:32:06.290 --> 00:32:07.420
And every app
developer is thinking

00:32:07.420 --> 00:32:09.462
like, well, this is
important for my application,

00:32:09.462 --> 00:32:11.050
so I should do it.

00:32:11.050 --> 00:32:13.750
And you put everything
together, and things get bad

00:32:13.750 --> 00:32:15.350
for the user.

00:32:15.350 --> 00:32:17.320
So as we see these
problems-- and this becomes

00:32:17.320 --> 00:32:19.300
a problem for everyone,
because if users

00:32:19.300 --> 00:32:22.240
aren't happy with Android, then
they're going to leave Android.

00:32:22.240 --> 00:32:24.380
They're going to not use
their devices as much.

00:32:24.380 --> 00:32:26.670
So we kind of need to
address this in the platform.

00:32:26.670 --> 00:32:29.430
So that's why we do these
kind of things where we say,

00:32:29.430 --> 00:32:33.030
OK, we can't let applications
run this freely anymore.

00:32:33.030 --> 00:32:35.778
We need to have some controls in
the platform to lock that down.

00:32:35.778 --> 00:32:37.320
Ultimately, it's
better for everyone.

00:32:37.320 --> 00:32:38.653
But it does cause a lot of pain.

00:32:38.653 --> 00:32:41.360
And it does cause
some restrictions

00:32:41.360 --> 00:32:43.220
on what developers
can do, but we

00:32:43.220 --> 00:32:48.290
try hard to still have as
much freedom as we can.

